    SECURITY FINDING: [M1] Improper Credential Usage — Hardcoded Credentials

    OWASP Mobile Top 10 2024: M1
    MASVS:  MSTG-STORAGE-14
    CWE:    CWE-798 (Use of Hard-coded Credentials)
    Risk:   CRITICAL

    DESCRIPTION:
    API keys, passwords, and encryption keys are embedded directly in strings.xml.
    This file is compiled into the APK and can be trivially extracted by any attacker:

    Attack steps:
    1. Download APK from Play Store (or get it via adb)
    2. Run: apktool d vulndroid.apk
    3. Open: res/values/strings.xml
    4. All credentials are visible in plaintext — no decompilation needed.

    Even with ProGuard/R8 obfuscation, strings.xml values are NOT obfuscated.
    They remain visible in the decompiled APK.

    REAL-WORLD IMPACT:
    - API key exposure → attacker can make authenticated API calls on your behalf
    - Admin password → direct backend access
    - Encryption key → decrypt any data the app has encrypted

    REMEDIATION:
    - Store secrets in environment variables injected at build time via BuildConfig
    - Use Android Keystore for runtime key generation — never store keys in code or resources
    - Use a secrets manager (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault) for backend keys
    - Rotate any key that was ever committed to source control
    - Use git-secrets or truffleHog in CI/CD to prevent future commits
-->
